<subSubSection id="C3246521FFE3FF9F32B7F9628F66F8D2" pageId="9" pageNumber="530" type="description">
<paragraph id="8B8136AAFFE3FF9F32B7F9628F66F8D2" blockId="9.[151,1437,1719,1889]" pageId="9" pageNumber="530">
Species of this group are small to medium sized, 
<quantity id="4CC69B4FFFE3FF9F30F4F9628944F962" box="[724,862,1719,1746]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.85" metricValueMax="9.5" metricValueMin="4.2" pageId="9" pageNumber="530" unit="mm" value="6.85" valueMax="9.5" valueMin="4.2">4.2–9.5 mm</quantity>
long. The proboscides lack hooked hairs, and the males usually lack projections in front of the mid coxae, except 
<taxonomicName id="4C3E4D29FFE3FF9F3148F90E89C5F946" authority="Holmberg, 1903" authorityName=": Strand" authorityYear="1910" box="[872,991,1755,1781]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Leptergatis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="530" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="romeroi">
<emphasis id="B94AEAB8FFE3FF9F3148F90E89C5F946" box="[872,991,1755,1781]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="530">A. romeroi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C3E4D29FFE3FF9F3636F90E8E8CF946" authorityName="Rodriguez &amp; Roig-Alsina. Scale" authorityYear="2004" box="[1046,1174,1755,1781]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Ancyloscelis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="530" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="saltensis">
<emphasis id="B94AEAB8FFE3FF9F3636F90E8E8CF946" box="[1046,1174,1755,1781]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="530">A. saltensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, with tuberculiform elevations. The vestiture is black and white to greyish in all the species (
<figureCitation id="13052A2FFFE3FF9F31BEF92A8E3FF8A9" box="[926,1061,1791,1818]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1741,1765]" captionTargetBox="[157,1431,725,1717]" captionTargetId="figure-221@10.[156,1432,725,1717]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 6. Females, A. apiformis species group, lateral view. A, A. apiformis (Fabricius). B, A. nigricornis Rodríguez &amp; Roig- Alsina. C, A. romeroi (Holmberg). D, A. saltensis Rodríguez &amp; Roig-Alsina. Scale lines = 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4897150" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4897150/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="530">Figs. 6A–D</figureCitation>
); the mestasomal apical bands are white, usually interrupted on T1, and the female tibial scopa has black hairs dorsally and white hairs ventrally. There are no synapomorphies uniting the group, which may be proved to be paraphyletic relative to the 
<taxonomicName id="4C3E4D29FFE3FF9F36FAF89D8F36F8D2" authorityName="Haliday" authorityYear="1836" box="[1242,1324,1864,1889]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Ancyloscelis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="530" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ursinus">
<emphasis id="B94AEAB8FFE3FF9F36FAF89D8F36F8D2" box="[1242,1324,1864,1889]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="530">ursinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
